{{infobox music festival | music_festival_name = World Festival of Black Arts | image = [[Image:fesmanlogo.gif]] | caption = World Festival of Black Arts (FESMAN) | location = [[Dakar, Senegal]]; [[Lagos, Nigeria]] | years_active = 1966, 1977, 2009/2010 | founders = [[Leopold Senghor]] | dates = December | genre = [[Pan-African]] | website = http://blackworldfestival.com }}
The '''World Festival of Black Arts''' (French: [[:fr:Festival Mondial des Arts Nègres|Festival Mondial des Arts Nègres]]), also known as '''FESMAN''', is a month-long culture and arts festival that takes place in [[Africa]]. The festival features poetry, sculpture, painting, music, cinema, theatre, fashion, architecture, design and dance from artists and performers from around the [[African Diaspora]].<ref>[http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90777/90856/6574894.html "World Festival of Black Arts launched at UN Headquarters"], ''People's Daily'', 15 January 2009.</ref>
==History== The festivals were planned as Pan-African celebrations, and ranged in content from debate to performance — particularly dance and theatre.<ref>Martin Banham, [[Errol Hill]], George Woodyard (eds), ''The Cambridge Guide to African & Caribbean Literature'', [[Cambridge University Press]], 1994; "''FESTAC''", p. 3.</ref>
===Dakar, 1966=== The First World Festival of Black Arts or '''World Festival of Negro Arts''' was held in [[Dakar]], Senegal, 1–24 April 1966, initiated by former President [[Leopold Senghor]], under the auspices of [[UNESCO]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/Ulis/cgi-bin/ulis.pl?catno=190260&gp=0&lin=1&ll=1|title=1st World Festival of Negro Arts, Dakar, April 1-24, 1966: Colloquium: Function and Significance of African Negro Art in the Life of the People and for the People, March 30-April 8, 1966; 1968|website=unesdoc.unesco.org|accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref> with the participation of 45 African, European, Caribbean, and North and South African countries, and featuring black literature, music, theater, visual arts, film and dance.<ref>[http://www.nypl.org/archives/3636 "First World Festival of Negro Arts. U.S. Committee Records"], New York Public Library.</ref> It was first state-sponsored festival to showcase the work of African and [[African diaspora|African diasporic]] artists, musicians and writers to a global audience.<ref>[http://www.tate.org.uk/learn/online-resources/glossary/w/world-festival-of-negro-arts "World Festival of Negro Arts"], Tate.</ref> Participants included historian [[Cheikh Anta Diop]]; dancers [[Arthur Mitchell (dancer)|Arthur Mitchell]] and [[Alvin Ailey]]; Mestre Pastinha, a [[Capoeira]] troupe from [[Bahia]]; [[Duke Ellington]]; [[Marion Williams]]; singers Julie Akofa Akoussah and [[Bella Bellow]]; writers [[Aimé Césaire]], [[Langston Hughes]], [[Wole Soyinka]], [[Amiri Baraka]], [[Sarah Webster Fabio]], and [[Nelson Mandela]].<ref>[https://continuo.wordpress.com/2009/11/25/dakar-1966-1er-festival-mondial-des-arts-negres/ "Dakar 1966 – 1er Festival Mondial des Arts Nègres"], Continuo, 25 November 2009.</ref> The filmmaker [[William Greaves]] made a 40-minute documentary of the event entitled ''The First World Festival of Negro Arts'' (1968).<ref>[http://www.africanfilmny.org/2012/the-first-world-festival-of-negro-arts/ "The First World Festival of Negro Arts"], African Film Festival, New York.</ref> Italian journalist [[Sergio Borelli]] produced ''Il Festival de Dakar (1966)''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/135843095|title=&quot;Festival mondial des arts n&egrave;gres&quot;- &quot;World Festival of Black Arts&quot; by Sergio Borelli, 50 min.|first=caterina|last=borelli|date=10 August 2015|publisher=|accessdate=8 March 2018|via=Vimeo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://musc265.blogs.wesleyan.edu/postcolonial/pan-african-festivals/|title=African Presences I: Music in Africa » Pan-African Festivals|website=musc265.blogs.wesleyan.edu|accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref> a 50-minute documentary for [[RAI]].
===Lagos, 1977=== {{Main|FESTAC 77}} In 1977, from 15 January to 12 February, the [[Festac '77|Second World Festival of Black Arts]] or '''Black and African Festival of Arts and Culture''' — known as '''FESTAC '77''' — took place in [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]], under the patronage of President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]].<ref name=Festac77>{{cite web|url=http://naijapositive.myfastforum.org/archive/festac-77-2nd-world-black-and-african-festival-of-arts__o_t__t_21.html|title=FESTAC '77 - 2nd World Black & African Festival of Arts - NaijaPositive.com|website=naijapositive.myfastforum.org|accessdate=8 March 2018}}</ref> Attended by more than 17,000 participants from over 50 countries, it was the largest cultural event ever held on the African continent.<ref name=Festac77 /> Among artists who took part were [[Stevie Wonder]], the [[Sun Ra Arkestra]], and [[Donald Byrd]] from the US, [[Tabu Ley]] and [[Franco Luambo Makiadi|Franco]] from the Congo, [[Gilberto Gil]] from Brazil, [[Bembeya Jazz National]] from Guinea, and [[Louis Moholo]], [[Dudu Pukwana]], and [[Miriam Makeba]] from South Africa.<ref>[http://blog.afropop.org/2011/01/history-of-world-festival-of-black-arts.html "The History of the World Festival of Black Arts & Culture / FESTAC"], Afropop Worldwide, 20 January 2011.</ref>
===Dakar, 2010=== The 2010 World Festival of Black Arts took place 10–31 December 2010, and was initiated by [[Senegalese President]] [[Abdoulaye Wade]] with the theme of [[African Renaissance]]. In President Wade's 2009 address at the UN, he said: "I call all Africans, all the sons and daughters of the Diaspora, all my fellow citizens, all the partners that are ready to walk by our side, all States, all international organizations, foundations, firms, etc. for a shining success for this Festival, and for the rise of a new Africa." It was curated by [[Kwame Kwei-Armah]], and participants at the opening ceremony included [[Youssou N'Dour]], [[Baaba Maal]], [[Angélique Kidjo]], [[Toumani Diabaté]], [[Wyclef Jean]], [[Carlinhos Brown]] and the [[Mahotella Queens]].<ref>[[Hannah Pool]], [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2011/jan/03/world-festival-of-black-arts-kwei-armah "World Festival of Black Arts: a once in a decade event"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 3 January 2011.</ref><ref name=NYT /> As well as music and cinema, the festival featured art exhibitions, theatre and dance performances, fashion shows, photography and other events, with the participation of artists and intellectuals from dozens of African and African diaspora countries, including the US, Brazil, Haiti, France and Cuba.<ref>Karima Daoudi, [http://fulbright.mtvu.com/karimadaoudi/2011/03/21/the-world-festival-of-black-arts-and-cultures/ "The World Festival of Black Arts and Cultures"], Fulbright-mtvU Fellows, 21 March 2011.</ref><ref name=NYT>Felicia R. Lee, [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/07/world-festival-of-black-arts-announces-lineup/?_r=0 "World Festival of Black Arts Announces Lineup"], ArtsBeat, ''[[The New York Times]]'', 7 December 2010.</ref>
